{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511920","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511920"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:47:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:47:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11815"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11815","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11815"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.1,0.37,0.05,0.26]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4420"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44849"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4420","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4420"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11815"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29736"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5438"},{"type":"tags","id":"5448"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6307"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6406"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44849"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA four week-old newborn is brought into her General Practice clinic with her mother.  She is aware that there are large number of vaccinations recommended for her child. Her wife recently injured herself at work and required a tetanus vaccination. She wants to know more about the tetanus vaccination and if it is appropriate for her child.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate information to give the mother?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Her child will only require four doses of the tetanus vaccine in the first 18 years of life","There are no risks associated with vaccination","The first tetanus vaccination typically covers six diseases in one injection","Tetanus-containing vaccines can not be co-administered with other vaccines","The first tetanus vaccination can be given from four weeks old"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETetanus is a disease caused by bacteria clostridium tetani and a complete series of the vaccination schedule provides almost 100% protection against the disease.  The bacteria is found in soil and animal faeces, and is transmitted via contaminated injuries.  Symptoms include lock jaw, stiff neck, difficulty swallowing, convulsions, arrythmia and cardiac arrest. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHer child will only require 4 doses of the tetanus vaccine in the first 18 years of life \u003C/strong\u003Eis not the most appropriate response. The Immunisation Handbook recommended a government-funded six-dose schedule with vaccinations given at 2, 4, 6 and 18 months, 4 years of age and adolescence (11- 13 years).  Wanning immunity however may require a booster depending on the type of wound and the age of last vaccination if a contaminated injury was to occur.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThere are no risks associated with vaccination \u003C/strong\u003Eis not the most appropriate response. Tetanus-containing vaccines have a similar side effect profile to most other vaccinations, including more minor effects such as headache, myalgia, lethargy and fever, but also a risk of more severe side effects such as anaphylaxis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe first tetanus vaccination typically covers six diseases in one injection \u003C/strong\u003Eis the most appropriate response. There is a wide range of tetanus-containing vaccines available, however, the recommended vaccine at two months of age is Infanrix\u00ae Hexa - which has coverage for Diphtheria, Haemophilus influenzae type b (Hib), Hepatitis B, Pertussis (whooping cough), Poliomyelitis, and Tetanus.  This minimises the number of needles needed to be administered to a child.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETetanus-containing vaccines can not be co-administered with other vaccines \u003C/strong\u003Eis not correct. Tetanus-containing vaccines can be co-administered with most other vaccines, however, this should be done at separate injection sites and not mixed in the same syringe as another vaccine.  \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe first tetanus vaccination can be given from four weeks old \u003C/strong\u003Eis not the most appropriate response. A tetanus-containing vaccine is recommended at two months of age, though can be given as early as six weeks.  At this age, a baby\u0027s immune system is mature enough to respond to the vaccination and develop protection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The vaccination schedule starts from two months of age (excluding Hepatitis B, which is typically offered at birth whilst in hospital)"],"references":["Tetanus. In: Immunisation handbook [online]. 2023. Available at: https://immunisationhandbook.health.gov.au/contents/vaccine-preventable-diseases/tetanus"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29736"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11815"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29736","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29736"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-05-05T00:21:51+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-05-05T00:21:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4420"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44849"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"